## Access Control Lists

For our third topic we are going to tackle what NSGs are but for the sake of having a better understanding of what they are in Azure we have to consult upon a few topics beforehand, first of which is the ACL.

An access control list is for our building like the list of people and the objects they carry to go in and out. But specifically it is a packet filter, a way to let traffic in or keep it out. This can be used alongside NAT where you should be able to figure out what kind of ID card or IP address needs to be changed from private to public so that it can communicate to the outside world. Its how your Azure services, at least the front facing ones that have to talk to the internet, get their private IP translated to the public one they have to use. The ACL has to have that private IP so it knows that said IP is part of the addresses that need to be translated.

These things are typically applied on a router to watch traffic going and coming. Some ACLs can be very specific, like just looking at either the source IP, destination IP and etc. Back to our analogy, every allowable list in your building has different rule provisions depending on how your list was written. However its not as simple as oh since its part of our list it is supposed to go through. It does not work that way. What happens is that it will consider whether to let a qualified ID card through or not depending on its rules.

### Tuples and Rule Combinations

A rule base in a firewall can be considered an access control list because it has a list of certain IPs allowed to qualify for rule comparison or just outright denied entirely. This combination of rules is called a tuple. For efficient and secure traffic flow, some people would combine multiple tuples to make a very specific access control rule.

### How ACL Rules Work

It starts from top to bottom. If the traffic it receives does not match the rule at the top it moves down and down until it has either found a match or no match. That is where implicit deny comes in. Since it did not follow any rule at all, why would we let this object be considered for entry into our building? We are not going to allow this ID card. These rules can be very general or very specific but usually the more specific ones go at the top.

