## Firewall Types

Now I was thinking whether or not to fully include all the nitty gritty details on this but I decided not to. However I will still mention the types of firewalls, what they do and where they work. At the very least this alongside the previous and next section will provide you a more appreciative understanding of the stuff we will do when it comes to network security groups.

### What a Firewall Actually Does

If you are connected to the internet, which is most likely since you are reading this from GitHub, you are most definitely using a firewall. A firewall in the most bare bones definition is something that controls the flow of network traffic. It can also be used to monitor and control incoming and outgoing corporate data for security and compliance reasons. It is also used to secure the user from accessing suspicious or otherwise not allowed content or sites and of course last but not least it is used to protect against malware, attacks and viruses.

### Network Based Firewalls

These are the traditional ones. Think of it as the old guard in the building where we are at, old but generally somewhat reliable. These kinds of firewalls will look at the port number. A port is like the endpoint of a software or a service, like a service endpoint in Azure where you will be connecting various of these to make sure your services can talk to each other.

They can also integrate other services like VPN so your security environment will be even more tightly locked down. They can also work as a network device of sorts and they are placed at the edge of the network so they control the flow of data within the network and its outward vicinity. It is like properly placing checkpoints near the entry points of your building so bad actors have a harder time getting in and causing damage.

### UTM and All-in-One Security Appliances

All you need to know is within the name. It is literally an all in one for protecting your network, covering things like inspecting malware, preventing spam, URL filtering so you can make sure no one is accessing sites they are not supposed to see and a bunch of other functions. Given their multifunctionality they can work at a variety of layers. However you cannot run all functions at the same time because the more features you enable the more processing power it consumes, so there is always a tradeoff between features and throughput. Running everything simultaneously would severely limit performance.

### Next Generation Firewalls

These ones are interesting because instead of just comparing the port number it looks at all the data in every packet. What does that mean? It can recognize who is sending the traffic, where it is being sent, what is in the application layer and with all of that it can then make forwarding decisions depending on those factors. Next gen is basically able to scan all of this traffic, figure out what kind of application is being used and then make said decisions.

It is also common for a next gen firewall to have a sort of list of known vulnerabilities that it can allow or block inside the firewall. The cool part is that its content filtering measures would allow you to not just rely on the URLs to block websites but on what kind of websites they might actually be.

### Web Application Firewalls

Now this is not like a normal firewall. It looks at the input being slotted into web-based applications and from there it will judge if it is allowed access or not. This is common for HTTP and HTTPS stuff so basically we are dealing with websites. It can determine if something is trying to input malicious data like an SQL injection and block that. This firewall alongside a next gen one is used for critical stuff like payment cards or healthcare.

