## Azure Relevant Information: Controlling Traffic Flows

Now naturally within a network all the stuff in it by default in Azure can talk to each other, even separate subnets. But this is a security and compliance problem. If everything can talk to each other there is no protection. If someone was able to compromise a resource or object they can do more damage. Also there are certain compliance standards companies must fulfill in terms of not only security but also privacy and how traffic is distributed instead of just one huge mess. So with that in mind here is a quick rundown of a few things that will definitely help you out. We will tackle the Microsoft Learn material later so we have plenty of time to learn the specifics.

### Azure Firewall

This is the next gen firewall equivalent but within the cloud. If you are managing a massive cloud architecture and you have cash to burn this is your go to. It has different tiers to handle the kinds of workloads but generally all of them share the same tendency to be enterprise grade solutions. You do not necessarily have the luxury to nitpick every single rule and whatnot so this is a force multiplier of sorts but of course it comes at a pretty penny.

### Network Security Groups

Now this is what you will be handling most of the time. It has inbound and outbound rules just like your regular firewall but unlike Azure Firewall it lacks more upper layer capability. It compensates by having two things: a high rule limit of 5000 and being free.

For the scale of a personal capstone project, architecture wise it is enough to fulfill a decent level of security. It just takes a bit of elbow grease and logical mapping to get it right but if you do you would basically be done with security and you just need to make sure all the networks are functioning by pinging them, but that is a different topic.

Quick tip: you can apply these at either the subnet or NIC level but preferably subnet. Why? It makes things easier to manage since whatever rule you impose is applied to all the stuff within that subnet.

### Service Tags

Remember when I mentioned that certain services need their own dedicated subnets? Service tags are your best friend when it comes to calibrating your NSGs around them. Instead of trying to find address ranges by yourself you can just look up their respective service tags and Azure will know which service you mean in regards to taking or giving data. Makes things easier and more efficient for you.

### Application Security Groups

Now this is not a different firewall but you can compare it to a service tag but for your own specific stuff that is not generally a considered cluster of a main service. So if you have a fleet of VMs you can assign this kind of tag on them so Azure will know which devices you mean. But bear in mind if you configure your rules these apply at the NIC level and not the subnet level so pay attention that your stuff does not overlap.

