## Microsoft Learn Section: Implement Security Groups

Now I want to add that aside from the stuff mentioned above, NSGs do not apply one to one to a subnet. They can be used to associate more than one subnet but each subnet can only be associated with one NSG. This is convenient for the reason that all of the rules you might have are going to be managed from one interface so the bulk of the work is at least more or less converged there. Although you do need to logically map everything correctly. Because if you look at it one way, why would you carelessly put your checkpoints all throughout your building without considering how your data moves inside? You have to consider how you want people to move inside your building.

### Determine Network Security Group Rules

Since these things help you filter traffic, the rules inside help a lot in making sure that traffic only flows the way it is supposed to. There are default rules in Azure and these rules have a priority number of 65000. Pretty big right? Well here logically the bigger the number the lower the priority, which means they are going to be enforced later than a rule sitting at say 2000. What you need to know is that custom rules can go from a priority number of 100 to 4096. Plenty of rules to come by. All of which are customizable as shown in the chart below:

```
Setting              Value
Source               Any, IP Addresses, My IP address, Service Tag, or Application Security Group
Source port ranges   Specify the ports on which the rule allows or denies traffic
Destination          Any, IP Addresses, Service Tag, or Application Security Group
Protocol             TCP, UDP, ICMP, ESP, AH, or Any
                     Note: ESP and AH are only available via JSON templates and PowerShell
Action               Allow or Deny
Priority             A value between 100 and 4096, unique for all security rules within the NSG
```

Also those default rules are impossible to delete so it is better to override them by putting a higher priority rule above them instead.

### Determine Network Security Group Effective Rules

There is a reason why it is recommended that you usually enforce your NSGs at the subnet level, like a standard operating procedure on how you should manage the checkpoints in your building. It allows you to manage things easier because if you set NSGs at the NIC level now you have to consider additional things like:

For inbound traffic, Azure first processes network security group rules for any associated subnets and then any associated network interfaces.

For outbound traffic, the process is reversed. Azure first evaluates network security group rules for any associated network interfaces followed by any associated subnets.

For both the inbound and outbound evaluation process, Azure also checks how to apply the rules for intra-subnet traffic, which refers to virtual machines communicating within the same subnet.

Now you might have a genuine reason why you want to put something at the NIC level, either to redirect your traffic more specifically or as a sort of pseudo quarantine where you still need to access the network but you cannot let something compromised interact with the healthy parts of your subnet. But generally you will be fine using an NSG at the subnet level.

Here are some key considerations from Microsoft Learn worth keeping in mind:

**Consider allowing all traffic.** If you place your virtual machine within a subnet or utilize a network interface, you do not have to associate the subnet or NIC with a network security group. This approach allows all network traffic through the subnet or NIC according to the default Azure security rules. If you are not concerned about controlling traffic to your resource at a specific level then do not associate your resource at that level to a network security group.

**Consider the importance of allow rules.** When you create a network security group, you must define an allow rule for both the subnet and network interface in the group to ensure traffic can get through. If you have a subnet or NIC in your network security group, you must define an allow rule at each level. Otherwise the traffic is denied for any level that does not provide an allow rule definition.

**Consider intra-subnet traffic.** The security rules for a network security group associated to a subnet can affect traffic between all virtual machines in the subnet. You can prohibit intra-subnet traffic by defining a rule in the network security group to deny all inbound and outbound traffic. This rule prevents all virtual machines in your subnet from communicating with each other.

**Consider rule priority.** The security rules for a network security group are processed in priority order. To ensure a particular security rule is always processed, assign the lowest possible priority value to the rule. It is good practice to leave gaps in your priority numbering such as 100, 200, 300 and so on. The gaps in the numbering allow you to add new rules without having to edit existing rules.

It always helps to actually know what is going on so you can either check out the effective security rules section of your NSG or use Azure Network Watcher.

### Augmented Security Rules

There are times where you do need to augment further your security rules and remember how when configuring your firewall you are supposed to make sure the specific rules are at the top? You can apply the same logic here.

A single network security group rule can contain multiple values in the Source, Destination and Service fields. This approach called augmented security rules reduces the total number of rules needed and simplifies NSG management.

Here is what you need to know about augmented security rules:

**Multiple IP addresses** — Combine multiple IP addresses into one rule.

**Multiple port ranges** — Specify multiple ports and ranges in the Service field.

**Service tags and ASGs** — Mix service tags, application security groups and IP addresses within the same rule.

**Reduced rule count** — Instead of creating separate rules for each IP range or port, combine them into fewer more manageable rules.

In enterprise environments with many IP ranges or services, augmented rules prevent NSG rule sprawl. For example instead of creating four separate rules for ports 80, 443, 8080 and 8090, create one rule with all the ports.

### Implement Application Security Groups

Application security groups help you structure and select your stuff more accurately. As mentioned before, instead of picking IP ranges you can just choose these tags instead so you have an easier time making up rules for them in your network security group.

Here are the advantages to implementing application security groups in your virtual networks:

**Consider IP address maintenance.** When you control network traffic by using application security groups, you do not need to configure inbound and outbound traffic for specific IP addresses. If you have many virtual machines in your configuration it can be difficult to specify all of the affected IP addresses. As you maintain your configuration the number of your servers can change and these changes can require you to modify how you support different IP addresses in your security rules.

**Consider no subnets.** By organizing your virtual machines into application security groups, you do not need to also distribute your servers across specific subnets. You can arrange your servers by application and purpose to achieve logical groupings.

**Consider simplified rules.** Application security groups help to eliminate the need for multiple rule sets. You do not need to create a separate rule for each virtual machine. You can dynamically apply new rules to designated application security groups. New security rules are automatically applied to all the virtual machines in the specified application security group.

**Consider workload support.** A configuration that implements application security groups is easy to maintain and understand because the organization is based on workload usage. Application security groups provide logical arrangements for your applications, services, data storage and workloads.

**Consider service tags.** Service tags represent a group of IP address prefixes from a specific Azure service. They help minimize the complexity of frequent updates on network security rules. While service tags are used to simplify the management of IP addresses for Azure services, ASGs are used to group VMs and manage network security policies based on those groups.

